05856nam a22007095i 9780674270121DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20212021mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742701217 a10.4159/97806742701212doi  a(DE-B1597)600627  a(OCoLC)1280944068  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aKF4558 7aLAW0180002bisacsh04a342.7308/52231 aBarnett, Randy E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Original Meaning of the Fourteenth Amendment :bIts Letter and Spirit /cRandy E. Barnett, Evan D. Bernick. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (432 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface: The Letter -- tIntroduction: The Letter and Spirit of the Fourteenth Amendment -- tPart I: The Privileges or Immunities of Citizenship Clause -- t1. The Early Origins of Privileges or Immunities -- t2. The Antislavery Origins of “Privileges or Immunities” -- t3. The Antislavery Origins of Republican Citizenship -- t4. Reconstructing National Citizenship -- t5. The Letter: Writing and Ratifying the Privileges or Immunities Clause -- t6. Enforcing Citizenship -- t7. Competing Originalist Interpretations -- t8. The Spirit: Implementing the Privileges or Immunities Clause -- tPart II: The Due Process of Law Clause -- t9. The Letter: The Original Meaning of “Due Process of Law” -- t10. The Spirit: Implementing the Due Process of Law Clause -- t11. The Proper Ends of Legislative Power -- tPart III: The Equal Protection of the Laws Clause -- t12. The Letter: The “Equal Protection of the Laws” -- t13. The Spirit: Implementing the Equal Protection of the Laws -- tConclusion: The Fourteenth Amendment in Full -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA renowned constitutional scholar and a rising star provide a balanced and definitive analysis of the origins and original meaning of the Fourteenth Amendment. Adopted in 1868, the Fourteenth Amendment profoundly changed the Constitution, giving the federal judiciary and Congress new powers to protect the fundamental rights of individuals from being violated by the states. Yet, according to Randy Barnett and Evan Bernick, the Supreme Court has long misunderstood or ignored the original meaning of the amendment’s key clauses, covering the privileges and immunities of citizenship, due process of law, and the equal protection of the laws. Barnett and Bernick contend that the Fourteenth Amendment was the culmination of decades of debates about the meaning of the antebellum Constitution. Antislavery advocates advanced arguments informed by natural rights, the Declaration of Independence, and the common law. They also utilized what is today called public-meaning originalism. Although their arguments lost in the courts, the Republican Party was formed to advance an antislavery political agenda, eventually bringing about abolition. Then, when abolition alone proved insufficient to thwart Southern repression and provide for civil equality, the Fourteenth Amendment was enacted. It went beyond abolition to enshrine in the Constitution the concept of Republican citizenship and granted Congress power to protect fundamental rights and ensure equality before the law. Finally, Congress used its powers to pass Reconstruction-era civil rights laws that tell us much about the original scope of the Amendment. With evenhanded attention to primary sources, The Original Meaning of the Fourteenth Amendment shows how the principles of the Declaration eventually came to modify the Constitution and proposes workable doctrines for implementing the key provisions of Section One of the Fourteenth Amendment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resourc